                <head>177. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>Shortly after 11 a.m. on February 17, Assistant Secretary of State <persName
                        corresp="#p_MLT1">Merchant</persName> briefed the Senate Foreign Relations
                    Committee on the situation in Europe with particular attention to the Berlin
                    question. After reviewing Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                        >Dulles</persName>’ trip to London, Bonn, and Paris and stating that he was
                    “entirely satisfied” with the results, <persName corresp="#p_MLT1"
                        >Merchant</persName> explained the positions of the British, French, and
                    West Germans on Berlin and described the meetings of the working group in
                    Washington. <persName corresp="#p_MLT1">Merchant</persName> stated further:
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“The Secretary feels very strongly that if the Soviets are convinced of
                            the firmness of the allied position to maintain its rights and position
                            in Berlin, and access thereto, then there will not be a physical
                            challenge on the part of the Soviets or the <gloss target="#t_GDR1"
                                >GDR</gloss> to the exercise of those rights.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>For text of <persName corresp="#p_MLT1">Merchant</persName>’s briefing and the
                    questions and answers which followed, see U.S. Senate, <hi rend="italic"
                        >Executive Sessions of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, 1959</hi>,
                    volume XI, pages 158–175.</p>
            </div>
